<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-05-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-05-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="111" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Italian
                                Chargé</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-05-15"><hi rend="italic">May 15,
                                1906</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 370.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In further reply to your note of the 24th
                            ultimo, I have the honor to inclose a copy of a letter from the
                            Secretary of Agriculture regretting that his department is unable to
                            grant a longer period than that fixed by F. I. D. 39, May 1, for the
                            importation, without the label “Artificially colored,” of Italian
                            colored pastes.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Bacon.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>